== 2. Senior Economist

=== Hierarchy Level
3-7 years of experience, independent researcher with established expertise

=== Key Activities and Responsibilities
- *Independent Research*: Leading research projects on specific economic themes (housing markets, labour dynamics, fiscal policy, commodity cycles)
- *Forecast Ownership*: Taking primary responsibility for forecasting specific economic variables
- *Model Development*: Building and maintaining proprietary econometric models
- *Client Engagement*: Participating in client calls, presenting at client events, responding to specific client queries
- *Policy Analysis*: Analyzing government policy proposals, budget measures, regulatory changes
- *Market Commentary*: Writing regular publications under own name, providing rapid response to major economic events
- *Mentorship*: Guiding junior economists, reviewing their analytical work
- *Cross-Team Collaboration*: Working with equity analysts, fixed income strategists, FX teams on sector-specific or thematic research

=== Required Skills

*Technical:*
- Advanced econometric modeling and forecasting techniques
- Deep knowledge of Australian economic data and institutional frameworks
- Understanding of monetary policy transmission mechanisms and central bank operations
- Expertise in specific economic domains (labour markets, property, fiscal policy, etc.)
- Ability to link economic analysis to market implications across asset classes
- Proficiency in programming for data analysis and visualization (R, Python)

*Interpersonal:*
- Strong written communication for client-facing research publications
- Confident presentation skills for client meetings and conferences
- Ability to translate complex economic concepts for non-technical audiences
- Collaborative approach to working across sales, trading, and research teams
- Professional networking with RBA, Treasury, and academic economists

*Regulatory:*
- Understanding of research governance and publication approval processes
- Knowledge of fair dealing obligations and managing conflicts of interest
- Awareness of market abuse regulations when providing time-sensitive economic analysis

=== Typical Work Modes

*Research & Analysis (50-60%):*
- Conducting economic research and developing differentiated views
- Building and refining econometric models
- Analyzing policy developments and their economic implications
- Writing detailed research reports and regular publications
- Monitoring economic data and updating forecasts

*Client Engagement (20-25%):*
- Participating in client calls and meetings
- Presenting at client events and conferences
- Responding to client questions on economic outlook
- Supporting sales team with economic insights for client discussions

*Collaboration & Communication (15-20%):*
- Working with equity analysts on sector implications of economic trends
- Collaborating with fixed income and FX strategists on positioning
- Contributing to firm-wide investment strategy discussions
- Mentoring junior economists

*Media & External (5-10%):*
- Media interviews and commentary (where firm permits)
- Speaking at industry conferences
- Engaging with RBA and Treasury officials
- Maintaining academic and professional networks

=== Career Progression Pathways

*Within Firm:*
- *Chief Economist*: Most senior economics role, setting firm's macro view and external representation (typically 8-12+ years total experience)
- *Head of Economic & Market Strategy*: Broader role combining economics with cross-asset strategy
- *Transition to Sales*: Senior relationship manager role leveraging economics expertise

*External Opportunities:*
- *Larger Broker/Bank*: Senior Economist or Chief Economist role at major investment bank (Macquarie, UBS, Morgan Stanley)
- *Buy-Side*: Macro strategist at fund manager, hedge fund, or superannuation fund
- *Central Bank*: Economist role at RBA (Economic Analysis, Financial Stability, Monetary Policy departments)
- *Government*: Senior economist at Treasury, Productivity Commission, or state government agencies
- *Consulting*: Senior economist at economic consultancy (Deloitte Access, Frontier, ACIL Allen)
- *Corporate*: Chief Economist at major corporation, industry association, or peak body

