== 3. Chief Economist

=== Hierarchy Level
8-15+ years of experience, most senior economics role and public face of firm's economic research

=== Key Activities and Responsibilities
- *Setting Firm's Economic View*: Determining firm's official economic forecasts, RBA/Fed policy calls, and macro market outlook
- *Thought Leadership*: Publishing regular high-profile economic commentary, defining firm's positioning on major economic debates
- *Client Engagement*: Presenting at major client events, hosting client roundtables, participating in client advisory boards
- *Media Spokesperson*: Representing firm in media interviews, serving as go-to expert for journalists on economic issues
- *Team Leadership*: Managing team of economists (typically 2-6 people), setting research priorities, developing talent
- *Cross-Firm Collaboration*: Working closely with equity research, fixed income strategy, FX teams to integrate economic view into investment recommendations
- *External Representation*: Speaking at industry conferences, participating in RBA/Treasury consultations, engaging with policymakers
- *Business Development*: Using economics platform to support client acquisition and retention, particularly with institutional investors

=== Required Skills

*Technical:*
- Expert-level macroeconomic knowledge across business cycles, monetary policy, fiscal policy, financial markets
- Deep understanding of central bank frameworks and policy transmission mechanisms
- Sophisticated grasp of linkages between economics, markets, and asset class performance
- Strong forecasting track record and ability to develop differentiated macro views
- Advanced econometric and quantitative analysis capabilities

*Interpersonal:*
- Executive presence and ability to command audience attention
- Exceptional communication skills across written, verbal, and visual formats
- Media training and comfort with live interviews under pressure
- Leadership and people management capabilities
- Networking skills with clients, media, policymakers, and peer economists

*Regulatory:*
- Expert understanding of research governance, disclosure requirements, and conflicts management
- Media policy compliance and approval processes
- Sophisticated awareness of market-sensitive information and fair dealing obligations
- Understanding of how economic commentary can move markets

=== Typical Work Modes

*Thought Leadership & Communication (40-50%):*
- Writing flagship economic publications and market commentary
- Media interviews (TV, radio, print, podcasts)
- Client presentations and keynote speeches
- Publishing regular outlook pieces and thematic research
- Social media engagement (LinkedIn, Twitter - where firm permits)

*Client & Business Development (25-30%):*
- Meeting with major institutional clients
- Presenting at client conferences and events
- Hosting client roundtables and economic briefings
- Supporting sales team on client pitches and renewals
- Participating in consultant/ratings meetings

*Team Leadership & Collaboration (15-20%):*
- Managing economics team and setting research priorities
- Reviewing team's research output and forecasts
- Collaborating with equity, fixed income, FX teams on cross-asset strategy
- Contributing to firm-wide investment committee
- Mentoring and developing team members

*Research & Analysis (10-20%):*
- Developing firm's economic forecasts and policy calls
- Conducting high-level strategic economic research
- Monitoring economic developments and adjusting views
- Engaging with RBA, Treasury, international economists

=== Career Progression Pathways

*Within Firm:*
- Typically the most senior economics role at brokerage level
- May transition to *Head of Research* (managing economics plus equity/fixed income research)
- Some move to *Head of Strategy* (broader cross-asset role)
- Occasionally move to *CEO* track (particularly at boutique research firms)

*External Opportunities:*
- *Chief Economist at Major Bank*: Senior role at Big 4 bank or Macquarie (significantly higher profile, resources, compensation)
- *Buy-Side CIO/Deputy CIO*: Chief Investment Officer or Deputy at fund manager, superannuation fund, or endowment
- *RBA*: Senior roles in Economic Analysis, Financial Stability, or policy-facing positions (Assistant Governor level)
- *Treasury*: Executive-level role in Macroeconomic Group or Markets Group
- *International Organization*: Senior economist at IMF, World Bank, OECD (typically requires PhD)
- *Consulting*: Partner/Director at major economic consultancy
- *Corporate Chief Economist*: Senior role at major corporation, industry association, or peak body
